notheistic convictions. Comparing Beowulf with its medieval German and Scandinavian analogues, The Art and Thought of the "Beowulf" Poet argues that the poem's uniqueness reflects one poet's coherent plan for the moral renovation of an amoral heroic tradition. In Beowulf, Neidorf discerns the presence of a singular mind at work in the combination and modification of heroic, folkloric, hagiographical, and historical materials. Rather than perceive Beowulf as an impersonally generated object, Neidorf argues that it should be read as the considered result of one poet's ambition to produce a morally edifying, theologically palatable, and historically plausible epic out of material that could not independently constitute such a poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEpic poetry, English (Old)xThemes, motives. 0aPoetry, MedievalxThemes, motives. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aScandinavia. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMedieval Germanic heroic literature, Old English Literature, Courtliness in Beowulf, Christianity and Paganism in Beowulf, Medieval epic poetry, reconciling pagan and Christian moralities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176692340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501766923423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501766923/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK